14":"1274–1314","1279–1338":"1279–1338","1281–Female":"1281–Deceased","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","about 1281":"about 1281","1274":"1274","1252":"1252","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","after 1314":"after 1314","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1279":"1279","1301":"1301","18 January 1301":"18 January 1301","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","Abt 1290":"about 1290","about 1274":"about 1274","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Astley, Warwickshire, England":"Astley, Warwickshire, England","Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Eastleigh,Essex,England":"Eastleigh, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Astley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places in England called Astley (in Lancashire, Shropshire, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, and Yorkshire), from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The modern surname seems to be particularly associated with the one in Warwickshire. See also   Astle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Astle","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cheshire called Astle, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. There may also have been some confusion with <i>Asthall</i> and   Astley  . Or occasionally this may be a topographic name denoting residence on an ‘east hill’ (from Middle English <i>ast</i> + <i>hill</i> or <i>hull</i>), i.e. a hill to the east of a settlement.","English: perhaps also a habitational name from Astwell, Northamptonshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>wielle</i> ‘spring’.","English: habitational name from Asthall, Oxfordshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook’."]}]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans 